  ' ============================================================
  ' MECHANISM
  ' ============================================================

  abstract class Mechanism {
    +getFunction(): Function
    +getReceptors(): Receptor[]
    +getEffectors(): Effector[]
  }

  note top of Mechanism
    **Primitive Semantics**:
    - Represents a system's capability to process input events
      (receptors) and produce output events (effectors).
    - An atomic causal unit of behavior within a system.
    - **DPR ↔ Behavior Anchor**: the correlation point between
      governance definitions (DPR) and observable behavior.
      - **Definition side**: structure deterministically derived from
        DPR (see Rule: Mechanism Auto-Definition Rule).
      - **Observation side**: DSM observes behavior; the Supervision
        plane compares observed vs. defined.
      - Unit of **Observation** (DSM compares observed vs.
        defined behavior).
    - **Positional semantics (GRS&CO)**: GRS&CO labels (Governor,
      Regulator, Supervisor, Coordinator, Operator) name **SIE's
      positional governance functions** — one per plane. They are
      SIE's own Systems (SIE-as-System), not Components composed
      by tenant Systems. The Mechanism subtypes (Controller,
      Actuator, Sensor) are operational infrastructure owned by
      tenant Systems.
    - **Governance authority (not composition)**: DPR artifacts are
      NOT structurally composed by Mechanisms — the generative
      direction reverses: DPR definitions → auto-define Mechanism
      definitions.

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - A mechanism MUST have at least one receptor and one effector.
    - If a mechanism is deleted, its receptors and effectors MUST be
      deleted.
    - If a receptor or effector is deleted, the mechanism MUST NOT be
      deleted, except if it is the last one the mechanism owns.

    **Notes**:
    - **Layer and plane placement**:
      - Governance plane (Reflexive): SIE Governor function.
      - Regulation plane (Reflexive): SIE Regulator function.
      - Supervision plane (Reflexive): SIE Supervisor function.
      - Coordination plane (Reflexive): SIE Coordinator function.
      - Operation plane (Ontic): SIE Operator function,
        Controller/Actuator/Sensor (Mechanism subtypes).
    - **Definition instance vs. operational instance**:
      - **Definition instance**: GSM primitive in Definition Manager
        (model artifact — does not execute).
      - **Operational instance**: runtime process instantiated FROM
        definition; same definition may have zero or more.
    - **Dual Definition Semantics (Ontic Layer)**:
      - **SIE definition**: SIE Operation plane instantiates and
        executes. Agency: SIE acts.
      - **Domain definition**: prescriptive definition of what a
        domain mechanism MUST be/do. Agency: Tenant acts, SIE
        oversees.
    - **Scope distinctions**:
      - Sensor (microscopic) vs. Supervision plane (macroscopic).
      - Actuator (microscopic) vs. Controller (macroscopic).
  end note


  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Mechanism : is
  Mechanism "1" o--> "1" Function : realizes
  Mechanism "1" *--> "1..*" Receptor : has
  Mechanism "1" *--> "1..*" Effector : has

  ' ============================================================
  ' RECEPTOR
  ' ============================================================

  class Receptor {
    +getReceivedEventArchetype(): EventArchetype
  }

  note top of Receptor
    **Primitive Semantics**:
    - Represents a mechanism's capability to receive events produced by
      mechanism's effectors.
    - Received events represent a cause for the mechanism to operate.
    - Multiple receptors can listen to the same EventArchetype, enabling
      fan-out patterns and cross-component coordination.

    **Auto-derivation**:
    Receptors MAY be auto-derived by the Definition Manager from
    Rule bodies (see Rule: Mechanism Auto-Definition Rule):
    - `on("A")` in Rule body → Receptor on the auto-derived
      Controller, bound to EventArchetype "A".
    - `sys.emit("A", data, response="B")` → Receptor on the
      auto-derived Controller, bound to response EventArchetype "B".
    - Closed-loop actuation (`var = sys.create/modify/delete/
      acquire(...)`) → sensing Receptor on the auto-derived
      Controller, bound to the ActuationSensingEvent archetype
      emitted by the auto-derived Sensor (see Sensing note).
    Auto-derived Receptors carry `derived_from_rule_id` and
    `derived=true`. Recomputed on Rule body change (body_hash diff).

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - A receptor MUST be bound to exactly one event archetype.
    - An event archetype MAY be bound to multiple receptors (sharing
      allowed).
    - If the bound event archetype is deleted, all receptors bound to
      it MUST be deleted.
    - If a receptor is deleted, the bound event archetype MUST NOT be
      deleted (other receptors may still reference it).
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Receptor : is
  Receptor "0..*" o--> "1" EventArchetype : receives

  ' ============================================================
  ' EFFECTOR
  ' ============================================================

  class Effector {
    +getEmittedEventArchetype(): EventArchetype
  }

  note top of Effector
    **Primitive Semantics**:
    - Represents a mechanism's capability to emit events.
    - Emitted events represent the effect of a mechanism's operation
      on the system.
    - Multiple effectors can emit the same EventArchetype, enabling
      distributed event emission and consistent event contracts.

    **Auto-derivation**:
    Effectors MAY be auto-derived by the Definition Manager from
    Rule bodies (see Rule: Mechanism Auto-Definition Rule):
    - `sys.emit("A", data)` → Effector on the auto-derived
      Controller, bound to EventArchetype "A".
    - `sys.create/modify/delete/acquire("A", ...)` → Effector
      on the auto-derived Controller, bound to an ActuationEvent
      archetype targeting StateObjectArchetype "A".
    Auto-derived Effectors carry `derived_from_rule_id` and
    `derived=true`. Recomputed on Rule body change (body_hash diff).

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - An effector MUST be bound to exactly one event archetype.
    - An event archetype MAY be bound to multiple effectors (sharing
      allowed).
    - If the bound event archetype is deleted, all effectors bound to
      it MUST be deleted.
    - If an effector is deleted, the bound event archetype MUST NOT be
      deleted (other effectors may still reference it).
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Effector : is
  Effector "0..*" o--> "1" EventArchetype : emits

  ' ============================================================
  ' INTERACTION
  ' ============================================================

  class Interaction {
    +getEffector(): Effector
    +getReceptor(): Receptor
  }

  note top of Interaction
    **Primitive Semantics**:
    - An **atomic causal coupling** from a producing effector to a
      receiving receptor — the primitive of causality in the system.
    - Every Interaction is carried by exactly one Channel. There is
      no channelless interaction: every causal influence requires a
      mediating medium (Shannon: Source→Transmitter→Channel→Receiver;
      Ashby: variety transmission requires coupling; physics: no
      action at a distance).
    - Interaction is medium-agnostic in its API: it declares *what*
      flows (Effector→Receptor), not *how* it flows. The Channel
      carries the Interaction, not the other way around. In DB
      terms, Interaction bears the FK to Channel; in the API,
      Channel navigates to its carried Interactions.
    - The Interaction API does not expose its Channel directly.
      Channel access to Interaction, not Interaction access to
      Channel. This preserves the semantic separation: Interaction
      is about causal coupling (what); Channel is about medium
      (how). Consumers that need to know the medium navigate from
      Channel.
    - An Interaction may be **intra-system** (both endpoints owned
      by the same System — internal coupling) or **cross-system**
      (endpoints owned by different Systems — requiring a
      Relationship as governance context). Both always have a
      Channel.

    **Cross-system Interaction semantics**:
    - The defining System owns the Interaction instance.
    - Both endpoints are referenced via aggregation (the Effector
      and Receptor may belong to different Systems).
    - The counterparty System MAY define a reciprocal Interaction
      from its perspective.
    - Cross-system Interactions without a Relationship between the
      owning Systems constitute a Supervision finding
      (ungoverned exchange).

    **Attributes Semantics**:
    - `effector`: The emitting endpoint producing an event instance.
    - `receptor`: The receiving endpoint consuming an event instance.

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - `effector` MUST be defined.
    - `receptor` MUST be defined.
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Interaction : is
  Interaction "0..*" o--> "1" Effector : has
  Interaction "0..*" o--> "1" Receptor :  has

  ' ============================================================
  ' CHANNEL
  ' ============================================================

  class Channel {
    +getInteractions(): Interaction[]
  }

  note top of Channel
    **Primitive Semantics**:
    - A **declared medium** through which Interactions are carried —
      the constraint on variety/information flow between endpoints.
    - Grounded in Shannon (channel capacity, noise), Ashby (variety
      transmission coupling), and Beer (organizational communication
      pathways with finite capacity and variety engineering).
    - Models *how* exchanges are carried (transport, capacity,
      protocol, reliability), not their meaning (*what* flows
      belongs to Interaction and EventArchetype).
    - Every Interaction is carried by exactly one Channel. A Channel
      carries one or more Interactions (multiplexing: one medium,
      many signals).
    - Directionality is a property of specific Interactions carried
      by the Channel, not of the Channel itself.

    **Cross-system Channel semantics**:
    - The defining System owns the Channel instance.
    - The counterparty System MAY define a reciprocal Channel
      from its perspective.
    - Cross-system Channels without a Relationship between the
      endpoint Systems constitute a Supervision finding
      (ungoverned connectivity).

    **Attributes Semantics**:
    - `interactions`: Interactions carried by the channel (stored;
      in DB, Interaction bears FK to Channel).

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - A Channel MUST carry at least one Interaction.

    **Derived content**:
    - **Interfaces**: derived from the Channel's Interactions.
      A Channel "connects to" the Interfaces that expose the
      Effectors/Receptors used by its Interactions:
        channelInterfaces(C) = { I ∈ Interface |
          ∃ interaction ∈ C.interactions :
          I.exposes(interaction.effector) OR
          I.exposes(interaction.receptor) }
    - **Cross-system**: derived from whether the Channel's
      Interactions have endpoints owned by different Systems.
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Channel : is
  Channel "1" *--> "0..*" Interaction : carries

  ' ============================================================
  ' INTERFACE
  ' ============================================================

  class Interface {
    +getName(): String
    +getReceptors(): Receptor[]
    +getEffectors(): Effector[]
  }

  note top of Interface
    **Primitive Semantics**:
    - A **named I/O surface** — a curated selection of Receptors
      and Effectors grouped into a coherent, addressable contact
      point on a Component.
    - Interface answers: WHICH of a Component's I/O ports form a
      coherent surface for external interaction, and what is that
      surface called?
    - This is a **structural design decision** — an explicit
      declaration of what is exposed, not a derivable consequence
      of wiring. Without Interface, there is no way to express
      "these Receptors/Effectors constitute my REST API" vs.
      "these are internal processing ports" prior to any
      Interaction being wired.
    - Interface is NOT a boundary or governance primitive.
      Governance boundaries are emergent from Constitution
      (Purpose + Directive define identity; identity implies
      boundary). Boundary governance semantics (what may cross,
      how variety is transformed) belong to DPR (Policies
      constraining exchange, Rules implementing crossing logic).
      Interface is purely structural: a named group of I/O ports.
    - **Boundary significance is supervision-derived**: an
      Interface becomes a governance-relevant boundary surface
      when it participates in cross-system Channels (derived
      from Interactions). This is an observation (Supervision
      plane), not a declaration.

    **Attributes Semantics**:
    - `name`: Human-readable semantic identifier for the I/O
      surface (e.g., "REST API", "Event Bus Listener",
      "Database Wire Protocol").
    - `receptors`: The Receptors selected for this surface.
    - `effectors`: The Effectors selected for this surface.

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - `name` MUST be mandatory and non-empty.
    - `name` MUST be maximum 80 characters long.
    - `name` MUST be unique among all interfaces of the same
      Component.
    - An Interface MUST contain at least one Receptor or one
      Effector (an empty surface is meaningless).
    - A Receptor/Effector MAY belong to multiple Interfaces
      (the same port can participate in multiple surfaces).
    - All Receptors/Effectors in an Interface MUST belong to
      Mechanisms owned by the same Component that owns the
      Interface.

    **Derived content**:
    - **Channels**: Channels whose Interactions reference
      Effectors/Receptors exposed by this Interface:
        interfaceChannels(I) = { C ∈ Channel |
          ∃ interaction ∈ C.interactions :
          I.exposes(interaction.effector) OR
          I.exposes(interaction.receptor) }
    - **Interactions**: the subset of those Channels'
      Interactions whose Effector or Receptor is exposed
      by this Interface.
    - **Internal vs. external**: derived from whether this
      Interface's Channels have Interactions with endpoints
      owned by different Systems.

    **Supervision-derived coherence findings**:
    - Interface with no participating Channels → orphaned I/O
      surface (warning).
    - External Interface (cross-system Channels) on a System
      with no Relationship to the counterparty System →
      ungoverned external surface (warning).
    - Receptor/Effector participating in cross-system
      Interactions but not selected by any Interface →
      undeclared external exposure (warning).
  end note

  SystemicPrimitive <|-- Interface : is
  Interface "1" o--> "0..*" Receptor : exposes
  Interface "1" o--> "0..*" Effector : exposes

  ' ============================================================
  ' GSM GOVERNANCE ARCHITECTURE ANALYSIS
  '
  ' Constraining vs Defining, Governance Axes, Qualifier
  ' Duality, and the Integrated Picture
  ' ============================================================

  note as GsmArchitectureAnalysis
    **GSM Governance Architecture Analysis**

    This note captures the design analysis of GSM's governance
    paradigm: the distinction between constraining and defining,
    the governance axes across all layers, the relationship
    between Qualifiers and Policies, and the resolution of
    whether structural definition requires new primitives.

    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    **1. CONSTRAINING vs DEFINING — foundational distinction**
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    These are two orthogonal governance modes, not synonyms:

    **Constraining** = declaring bounds on a possibility space
    (reducing variety, Ashby). Declarative. "This property must
    hold." Does NOT produce the thing — only bounds its
    acceptable range. The thing must exist independently.

    **Defining** = establishing existence, content, or logic
    (selecting specific variety). Generative. "This IS."
    Produces the thing itself.

    They compose orthogonally: you can constrain something
    that is defined, and define something that is constrained.

    **Where DPR sits:**

    | DPR Level   | Mode        | What it does                    |
    |-------------|-------------|---------------------------------|
    | Directive   | Constrains  | Quality direction on Purpose    |
    | Policy      | Constrains  | Measurable bound/spec (any axis)|
    | Rule        | Defines     | Behavioral logic (imperative)   |

    The Policy → Rule transition is simultaneously:
    - A **modality step-down** (declarative → imperative)
    - A **mode transition** (constraining → defining)
    - An **axis narrowing** (any axis → behavioral axis only)

    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    **2. GOVERNANCE AXES — what kinds of things are governed**
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    GSM recognizes six governance axes, each targeting a
    different kind of system property:

    | Axis         | Question                               | Primitives                                      |
    |--------------|-----------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------|
    | Teleological | WHY does the system exist?              | Purpose, Directive                               |
    | Functional   | WHAT can the system do?                 | Function                                         |
    | Behavioral   | HOW does the system act on events?      | Rule, Actuation, Sensing                         |
    | Structural   | WITH WHAT is the system built?          | Component, Mechanism, Interface, Channel, R/E    |
    | Relational   | WITH WHOM does the system connect?      | Relationship, Role                               |
    | Epistemic    | WHAT does the system know about?        | EventArchetype, StateObjectArchetype             |

    Policy predicates can reference properties across ALL axes
    (structural, behavioral, epistemic, relational). This is
    why Policy is the **universal constraining construct**:
    axis-agnostic, measurable, declarative.

    Rule operates on ONE axis only: behavioral. Its Starlark
    body is a process definition, not a property assertion.

    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    **3. POLICY IS THE UNIVERSAL CONSTRAINING CONSTRUCT**
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    Policy constrains properties across ALL governance axes.
    The difference between constraining and specifying a
    property reduces to the operator:

    - **Constraint**: `Component.replicas >= 2` (inequality)
    - **Specification**: `Component.replicas == 3` (equality)

    Both are valid Policy predicates. Both are declarative,
    measurable, appraised by Supervision, and traceable through
    Operationalization.

    Policy constraining examples (axis-agnostic):
    - Quality constraints: `Service.integrity >= 0.99`
    - Structural bounds: `Component.replicas >= 2`
    - Configuration bounds: `Controller.maxRetries >= 2`
    - Relational properties: `Relationship.sla.uptime >= 0.99`
    - Epistemic properties: `EventArchetype.schema.version ==
      "2.0"`

    No axis-specific constraint primitives are needed.

    **Conflation warning — Policy `==` as disguised definition:**

    When Policy uses equality (`Controller.maxRetries == 3`),
    it conflates constraint and definition in one artifact.
    The operator `==` is formally a constraint (bounds the
    acceptable space to a single point), but functionally acts
    as a definition (specifies the value). This causes:
    - **Change velocity mismatch**: changing a value ("set
      retries to 5" — operational) requires changing a Policy
      (governance-plane artifact with Regulation review).
    - **Ownership confusion**: "minimum retries for
      reliability" is a governance decision (slow); "how many
      retries" is an operational decision (fast).
    - **Loss of orthogonality**: constraining and defining
      become inseparable in the same artifact.

    See §9 (DPQ exploration) for a resolution that preserves
    the constraining/defining separation.

    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    **4. WHY NO "STRUCTURAL RULE" IS NEEDED**
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    **Behavior is a PROCESS** — it requires imperative
    definition (event trigger → conditional logic → sys.* calls
    → state mutation). Only executable logic can define behavior.
    Hence Rule exists: an imperative, computational body.

    **Structure is STATE** — expressible as declarative property
    assertions. "This Mechanism MUST have 3 replicas" is a
    property statement, not a computation. There is no event
    trigger, no conditional branch, no execution step. A
    "structural Rule" would be a degenerate Rule with no
    computational body — just a property assignment.

    That degenerate form already exists: it is a Policy with an
    equality predicate. `Controller.maxRetries == 3` IS the
    "structural definition" — it specifies the exact value
    without imperative logic.

    **The declarative/imperative boundary applies ONLY to
    behavior:**
    - Constitution: declarative (Purpose, Directive)
    - Organization: declarative (Policy) + imperative (Rule,
      for behavior only)
    - Infrastructure: governed by Policy predicates targeting
      structural properties (declarative)

    The DPR chain therefore has two sub-chains with different
    terminal modalities:
    - **DP** (Directive → Policy): constraining gradient.
      Declarative. Axis-agnostic. Terminates at Policy for
      structural governance.
    - **DPR** (Directive → Policy → Rule): constraining-then-
      defining gradient. Declarative → imperative. Terminates
      at Rule for behavioral governance.

    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    **5. THE QUALIFIER DUALITY — governance gap**
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    **The semantic family of "qualifier":**

    Three concepts share the root "qualifier" / "quality":

    | Concept                   | Level        | Function                                |
    |---------------------------|--------------|-----------------------------------------|
    | purposeQualifier (String) | Constitution | **Names** a quality dimension            |
    | Policy predicate          | Organization | **Constrains** the dimension             |
    | SystemicPrimitiveQualifier| Meta-model   | **Defines** a value on a primitive       |

    These form a governance gradient on the SAME quality
    property:
      purposeQualifier (names it) → Policy (bounds it)
      → Qualifier.value (defines it)

    **The governance gap**: only the first two steps are
    connected via Operationalization. Qualifier.value is
    disconnected from DPR — no governance lineage, no
    appraisal, no coherence check against Policies constraining
    the same property.

    Example of the gap:
    - Policy: `Controller.maxRetries >= 2` (DPR-governed)
    - Qualifier: `{"maxRetries": 3}` (ungoverned, parallel)
    - Same property, two representations, no coherence link.

    **Coexistence of constraining and defining:**

    The gap reveals that constraining (Policy) and defining
    (Qualifier) are orthogonal operations on the same property.
    All four combinations are valid:

    | Constrained? | Defined? | Meaning                     |
    |:---:|:---:|--------------------------------------------|
    | No  | No  | Property in schema but unused              |
    | No  | Yes | Value defined, ungoverned → gap finding    |
    | Yes | No  | Bounds set, no value yet → spec gap        |
    | Yes | Yes | **Complete governance**: bound + value      |

    Defining without constraining is legitimate (the system
    HAS this value; governance hasn't opined yet). Constraining
    without defining is legitimate (governance says "at least
    2" but no operational value chosen yet).

    **Two competing resolutions (evaluated):**

    The SystemicPrimitiveQualifier mechanism serves TWO
    distinct functions:

    (a) **Ontological extension** (schema extensibility):
        QualifierArchetype schemas define WHAT PROPERTIES CAN
        EXIST on a primitive — domain-specific vocabulary.
        NOT governance-active; it is structural vocabulary.
        **This remains as is in both resolutions.**

    (b) **Governance-active property values**:
        Qualifier.value stores property values that may carry
        governance intent (retryPolicy, maxRetries, timeoutMs).

    **Resolution A — migrate to Policy `==`:**
    Governance-active configuration expressed as Policy
    equality predicates (`Controller.maxRetries == 3`).
    Qualifier retains only purely epistemic metadata.
    - Pro: simple, no new mechanism.
    - Con: conflates constraint and definition (see §3
      conflation warning). Operational value changes
      require governance-plane Policy changes.

    **Resolution B — DPQ (Directive → Policy → Qualifier):**
    Qualifier values stay as first-class definition atoms,
    governed through DPQ chains (see §9). Policy constrains;
    Qualifier defines. Each follows its own governance
    process with its own change velocity.
    - Pro: preserves constraining/defining orthogonality.
    - Pro: different change dynamics (governance vs.
      operational).
    - Con: more complex model; requires Qualifier governance
      lifecycle and Operationalization linkage.

    **Resolution B is more systemics-aligned** (separation of
    governance and operational concerns, different change
    velocities) but requires model evolution. See §9 for full
    exploration.

    **Definitional relevance test (all GSM qualifiers):**
    GSM is the definition model. All content SHOULD be
    definitionally relevant. Test: would this property produce
    governance effects (be referenced by a Policy)?
    - YES → definitional → GSM (e.g., technology, maxRetries)
    - NO → classificatory → DSM (e.g., industry, department)
    This aligns with the existing "no classification in GSM"
    argument. Purely classificatory qualifiers should migrate to
    DSM; definitionally relevant qualifiers stay in GSM.

    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    **6. CONTROLLER IN OPERATIONALIZATION — RESOLVED: NO**
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    The TODO question asked: "Should Controller be added to the
    Operationalization chain (Directive → Policy → Rule →
    Controller)?"

    **Answer: No.** With governance-active qualifier
    configuration migrating to Policies:

    1. **Controller properties are already governed by
       Policies** that target Controller archetype properties
       in their predicates. Those Policies ARE in the
       Operationalization chain (Directive → Policy).

    2. **Controller.implements(Rule)** provides structural
       traceability from governance to infrastructure. This
       is a realization link (HOW), not a governance lineage
       link (WHY).

    3. **Extending Operationalization** would conflate the
       governance lineage axis (WHY: Directive → Policy →
       Rule) with the structural realization axis (HOW: Rule
       → auto-derives → Controller). These are different
       questions that use different navigation paths.

    4. **"What Policies govern this Controller?"** is
       answerable by: find Policies whose predicates reference
       Controller archetype properties. No Operationalization
       extension needed.

    Operationalization remains: Directive → Policy → Rule.
    The Controller is the TARGET of governance, not a node
    in the governance lineage.

    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    **7. INTEGRATED PICTURE — the complete GSM governance map**
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    **Layers × Axes × Modes:**

    | Layer          | Governance Mode            | Primitives                                    |
    |----------------|----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|
    | Constitution   | Anchoring (teleological)   | Purpose (defines), Directive (constrains)     |
    | Organization   | Constraining (declarative) | Policy (any axis), Operationalization (trace) |
    |                | Defining (imperative)      | Rule (behavioral)                             |
    |                | Defining (authored)        | Function, Relationship, Component (compose)   |
    |                | Defining (epistemic)       | EventArchetype, StateObjectArchetype          |
    |                | Defining (auto-derived)    | Actuation, Sensing                            |
    | Infrastructure | Realizing (auto-derived)   | Controller, Actuator, Sensor, R/E             |
    |                | Realizing (authored)       | Mechanism, Interaction, Channel, Interface    |

    **The three navigation paths:**

    1. **Operationalization** (governance lineage — WHY):
       Directive → Policy → Rule
       "Why does this Rule exist?"
       Traces normative authority from identity to behavior.

    2. **Auto-derivation** (structural production — HOW built):
       Rule body → Controller + Actuator + Sensor + R/E
       "What infrastructure does this Rule produce?"
       Traces behavioral definition to structural realization.

    3. **Policy targeting** (structural governance — governed):
       Policy predicate → any archetype property
       "What constraints apply to this infrastructure?"
       Traces governance to structural targets.

    **Rule is the nexus** where:
    - Path 1 terminates (governance lineage arrives)
    - Path 2 departs (infrastructure auto-derives)
    - Path 3 connects laterally (Policies constrain both
      Mechanism-realized Functions and auto-derived infrastructure)
    - Value delivery is structurally traceable: Function ←
      Mechanism/Controller → Rule → Operationalization →
      Directive → Purpose

    **The complete DPR governance chain:**

    For BEHAVIOR (declarative → imperative):
      Purpose ← Directive → Policy → Rule → (auto-derives)
      Controller → Actuator/Sensor → R/E → Mechanism

    For STRUCTURE (declarative throughout):
      Purpose ← Directive → Policy → (predicates target)
      Component, Mechanism, Interface, Channel properties

    The same Directive can operationalize through BOTH
    sub-chains: one Policy constraining behavior (via Rule),
    another Policy specifying structural properties directly.
    Both appear in Operationalization. Both are appraised.

    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    **8. REMAINING DESIGN FRONTIERS (open)**
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    (a) **Relationship teleological traceability**: Relationship
        has no explicit DPR lineage — "why does this
        Relationship exist?" is not traceable through
        Operationalization. Acceptable for now;
        Supervision detects Relationships without corresponding
        cross-system Channels.

    (b) **Function → Mechanism derivability**: Function is now
        directly referenced by Mechanism (1:1). The structural
        chain Function ← Mechanism/Controller → Rule provides
        value delivery traceability without a dedicated
        primitive.

    (c) **Qualifier scope reduction**: if governance-active
        configuration migrates to Policy (Resolution A) or
        becomes a governed DPQ atom (Resolution B), the
        residual ungoverned Qualifier scope (purely epistemic
        metadata) may overlap with the existing "no
        classification in GSM" principle. Evaluate whether
        the remaining Qualifier use cases are consistent with
        GSM's generative nature or should migrate to DSM.

    (d) **Policy predicate property resolution**: Policy
        predicates reference archetype property paths. The
        Definition Manager must resolve property references
        against both archetype schemas AND qualifier archetype
        schemas. This is an engineering requirement, not a
        model change.

    (e) **DPQ model decision**: §9 explores DPQ but does not
        resolve it. Key remaining questions:
        - How does Operationalization accommodate a Qualifier
          terminal? (extend existing or new tracing primitive?)
        - Does Qualifier need its own definition lifecycle
          (SystemicPrimitiveDefinitionStatus) or inherit from
          its parent primitive?
        - Engineering: how does the Definition Manager validate
          Qualifier values against Policy predicates at save
          time?

    (f) **Policy classification by predicate target**: §11
        formalizes the deterministic triple classification
        (behavioral / structural-defined / structural-emergent).
        Remaining questions:
        - Should Policy carry a derived `governanceCategory`
          field (BEHAVIORAL / STRUCTURAL_DEFINED /
          STRUCTURAL_EMERGENT) or is this purely a query-time
          derivation?
        - How does dual governance (same Policy in both DPR
          and DPQ) interact with Operationalization? Does the
          same Policy appear in two chains with different
          terminals?

    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    **9. DPQ EXPLORATION — structural/property definition atom**
    **(OPEN — design exploration, not resolved)**
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    **The gap in the current model:**

    The DPR chain has a behavioral definition atom (Rule) but
    no structural/property definition atom. For structural
    governance, the chain is:
      Directive → Policy → ??? (where is the value?)

    The current §4 resolved this as "Policy `==` handles
    structural specification." But §3 identified that this
    conflates constraint and definition. The gap:

    | Governance need       | Constraining                | Defining                  |
    |-----------------------|-----------------------------|---------------------------|
    | Behavior              | Policy (declarative)        | Rule (imperative)         |
    | Structure / property  | Policy (declarative)        | **??? (gap)**             |

    **DPQ fills the gap with Qualifier as definition atom:**

    | Chain | Terminal atom | Atom modality | Produces          |
    |-------|---------------|---------------|-------------------|
    | DPR   | Rule          | Imperative    | Behavioral logic  |
    | DPQ   | Qualifier     | Declarative   | Property value    |

    Both share the **DP** constraining root
    (Directive → Policy). They fork at the definition level:
    - Rule: behavioral definition (event-triggered logic)
    - Qualifier: structural/property definition (JSON value)

    **Concrete example — DPQ in action:**

    - Directive: "System MUST ENSURE availability OF
      data-persistence"
    - Policy: `Database.replicas >= 3` (bounds)
    - Qualifier: `{"replicas": 5}` (value within bounds)
    - Supervision: checks `5 >= 3` → compliant ✓

    If operational needs change (scale to 7 replicas):
    - Change Qualifier only (operational decision, fast)
    - Policy unchanged (governance decision, stable)
    - Supervision re-checks: `7 >= 3` → still compliant ✓

    Compare with Policy-only model (Resolution A):
    - Policy: `Database.replicas == 5`
    - Scale to 7 → change Policy (governance process, slow)
    - Or: two Policies `>= 3` (constraint) and `== 5` (spec)
      — redundant and conflict-prone.

    **DP → {R, Q} — the complete definitional grammar:**

    ```
    DP (constraining gradient — declarative, universal):
      Directive → Policy

    DPR (behavioral definition — imperative, code):
      DP → Rule → (auto-derives) Controller/Actuator/Sensor

    DPQ (structural/property definition — imperative, data):
      DP → Qualifier.value → (stored on) SystemicPrimitive
    ```

    DP is the common constraining root. It forks into two
    definition atoms:
    - **Rule**: what to DO on events (behavioral axis)
    - **Qualifier**: what this IS (all non-behavioral axes)

    Both are **governance-imperative**: acts of definition that
    select specific variety within Policy bounds. They differ
    only in technical representation (Starlark code vs. JSON
    data) and governance axis (behavioral vs. structural).

    Together, Rule + Qualifier cover the full axis space for
    DEFINITION, while Policy covers it universally for
    CONSTRAINING.

    Note: §11 extends this binary fork into a triple
    classification (DPR / DPQ / DP-only) and shows that the
    fork is **deterministic** — determined by static analysis
    of the Policy predicate target. It also identifies a
    third category (structural-emergent) where DP terminates
    at Policy with no definition atom needed.

    **Qualifier definitional scope in this model:**

    Under DPQ, Qualifier content falls into three categories:

    | Category | Example                       | In GSM? | Governed? |
    |----------|-------------------------------|:-------:|:---------:|
    | Governance-active  | {"replicas": 3}     | Yes     | Yes (DPQ) |
    | Definitional but   | {"technology": "PG"} | Yes     | Maybe     |
    | ungoverned         |                       |         | (gap)     |
    | Classificatory     | {"industry": "fin"} | **No**  | No → DSM  |

    **The "no classification in GSM" argument still holds:**
    classificatory qualifiers are descriptive opinion, not
    definitional — they belong to DSM. All remaining GSM
    qualifiers should be definitionally relevant (would a
    Policy reference this property?).

    **§4 update — still no "structural Rule":**

    DPQ does NOT contradict §4. There is still no need for a
    "structural Rule" (imperative executable logic for
    structural definition). Qualifier defines values as JSON
    data, not executable logic — but this is a **technical
    modality** difference, not a governance modality
    difference.

    Both DPR and DPQ share the same governance modality
    transition:
    - DP (declarative: constraining) → Rule (imperative:
      defining behavior — expressed as code)
    - DP (declarative: constraining) → Qualifier (imperative:
      defining value — expressed as data)

    The constraining → defining transition occurs at the
    SAME structural point in both chains: the fork from
    Policy to the terminal atom.

    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    **10. RULE↔POLICY vs QUALIFIER↔POLICY — relationship types**
    **(OPEN — design exploration)**
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    **Policy→Rule: ENFORCEMENT relationship**

    - Policy declares a constraint
    - Rule defines behavioral logic that operationalizes the
      constraint as imperative system behavior
    - The Rule's body is NOT derivable from the Policy
    - The Rule adds entirely new information (event trigger,
      conditional logic, state mutations)
    - Verification is **indirect**: the Supervision plane
      observes behavioral outcomes and compares with Policy
      (observation-time — requires runtime evidence)
    - Multiple radically different Rules could operationalize
      the same Policy
    - Rule may operationalize zero, one, or multiple Policies

    Concrete mapping:
    - Policy: `Order.total == sum(lineItems[*].subtotal)`
    - Rule: on("OrderSubmitted") → validate → reject
    - The Rule DEFINES the behavioral response to an event.
      The Rule exists because the Policy exists — without the
      Policy, there is no reason for the validation logic.
      But the Rule is a design-time definition, not a runtime
      enforcement mechanism. The Operation plane executes the
      Rule; the Supervision plane verifies Policy compliance.

    **Policy→Qualifier: SATISFACTION relationship**

    - Policy declares a constraint on a property's value space
    - Qualifier provides a specific value **within those bounds**
    - The Qualifier's content IS partially constrained by the
      Policy (must satisfy the predicate)
    - Verification is **direct**: evaluate Policy predicate
      with Qualifier value → boolean (definition-time —
      value is known at save/parse)
    - Multiple values could satisfy the same Policy (bounded
      set)
    - A Qualifier value may satisfy zero, one, or multiple
      Policies

    Concrete mapping:
    - Policy: `Database.replicas >= 3`
    - Qualifier: `{"replicas": 5}`
    - The value 5 EXISTS within the bound ≥ 3. Without the
      Policy, the value can be anything (ungoverned).

    **Comparison summary:**

    | Aspect            | Rule ← Policy      | Qualifier ← Policy  |
    |-------------------|---------------------|----------------------|
    | Relationship type | ENFORCEMENT         | SATISFACTION         |
    | Axis relation     | Cross-axis          | Same-axis            |
    | Content derivable | No (new info)       | Partially (bounded)  |
    | Verification      | Observation-time    | Definition-time      |
    | Change coupling   | Loose               | Tight (value space)  |

    Both are **governance lineage** — both answer "why does
    this definition exist?" Both are traceable through
    Operationalization. Both are appraised by Supervision.
    Both are **design-time definitions** — neither enforces
    anything at runtime. The Operation plane executes; the
    Supervision plane verifies.
    They capture different KINDS of definitional
    relationships: enforcement (behavioral) vs. satisfaction
    (structural/property).

    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    **11. POLICY CLASSIFICATION BY PREDICATE TARGET**
    **(deterministic routing to governance terminal)**
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    The DP → {R, Q} fork (§9) is not arbitrary — it is
    **determined by what the Policy's predicate targets**.
    The predicate target dictates the governance response:
    what kind of definition atom (if any) is needed to
    satisfy or enforce the constraint.

    **Critical framing — all chains are definition-time:**

    DPR, DPQ, and DP-only are ALL Definition-plane artifacts.
    None of them "enforce at runtime." The distinction is
    NOT when things happen (all definition-time), but:
    - What KIND of definitional response does the constraint
      require? (Rule / Qualifier / none)
    - When can the Supervision plane VERIFY compliance?
      (observation-time / definition-time)

    The Operation plane executes (realizes definitions).
    The Supervision plane verifies (evaluates Policies
    against evidence). DPR and DPQ only DEFINE — they
    produce the artifacts that Operation realizes and
    Supervision verifies. Confusing Definition with
    Operation or Supervision breaks the closed-loop plane
    boundaries.

    **Three Policy categories (deterministic):**

    | Category | Predicate targets | Definitional response | Verification availability | Chain |
    |---|---|---|---|---|
    | Behavioral | SOA properties, event dynamics | Rule (imperative) | Observation-time | DPR |
    | Structural-defined | Qualifier properties on any SP | Qualifier (declarative) | Definition-time | DPQ |
    | Structural-emergent | Graph properties (cardinality, topology) | — (none) | Definition-time | DP |

    **Verification availability** clarifies WHEN the
    Supervision plane has sufficient evidence to evaluate:
    - **Observation-time**: requires evidence from the State
      plane (state object instances, event flow). Supervision
      cannot verify until the system is operating.
    - **Definition-time**: verifiable at save/parse time from
      the definition graph (Qualifier values or structural
      properties are known when authored).

    This is a SUPERVISION concern, not a Definition concern.
    Both DPR and DPQ are definition-time. The Policy does
    not "know" when it will be verified — it only declares
    what must hold.

    **Category 1 — Behavioral Policies (DPR)**

    Target: **StateObjectArchetype properties** and runtime
    dynamics (event flow, sequencing, mutation invariants).

    These constrain properties that **exist only at runtime**
    — state object instances in the state plane. The
    Supervision plane cannot verify at definition-time
    because the governed property depends on event-driven
    dynamics that require runtime evidence.

    Governance response: **Rule** (imperative behavioral
    logic), which DEFINES how the system acts on events —
    what triggers it, what conditions it evaluates, what
    state mutations it performs.

    Why Rule: the constraint requires **creative behavioral
    information** — which event triggers it, what conditional
    logic applies, which sys.* calls define behavior. This
    information is NOT derivable from the Policy. The Rule
    adds entirely new information (§10: ENFORCEMENT).

    **The Rule does NOT "enforce" the Policy at runtime.**
    The Rule DEFINES behavioral logic (Definition plane).
    The Operation plane EXECUTES the Rule (Ontic layer).
    The Supervision plane VERIFIES whether the executed
    behavior satisfies the Policy (Reflexive layer,
    observation-time). These are three distinct functions
    across three distinct planes — conflating them breaks
    the closed-loop governance boundaries.

    Examples:
    - `Order.total == sum(lineItems[*].subtotal)` →
      Rule: on("OrderSubmitted") → validate → reject
    - `Payment.status != "processed" UNTIL
      Validation.status == "passed"` →
      Rule: on("PaymentRequest") → check validation →
      block/proceed

    Change dynamics: Policy changes slowly (governance
    decision); Rule changes at behavioral-logic velocity
    (how to act). Different concerns, different owners.

    **Category 2 — Structural-Defined Policies (DPQ)**

    Target: **Qualifier properties** on any SystemicPrimitive
    (not limited to infrastructure — qualifiers exist on
    Components, Functions, Purposes, Relationships, etc.).

    These constrain properties that **are authored at
    definition-time** as Qualifier values (JSON). The
    Supervision plane can verify at save/parse time by
    evaluating the Policy predicate against the Qualifier
    value.

    Governance response: **Qualifier** (declarative value),
    which provides a specific value within the bounds set by
    the Policy.

    Why Qualifier: the constraint requires only a **parametric
    value selection** within a bounded space — no event
    trigger, no conditional logic, no imperative computation.
    The value partially follows from the constraint
    (§10: SATISFACTION).

    Examples:
    - `Database.replicas >= 3` →
      Qualifier: {"replicas": 5} (value within bounds)
    - `Controller.maxRetries >= 2` →
      Qualifier: {"maxRetries": 3} (value within bounds)
    - `Function.maxConcurrency <= 100` →
      Qualifier: {"maxConcurrency": 50}

    Change dynamics: Policy changes slowly (governance
    constraint); Qualifier changes at operational velocity
    (which value to choose within bounds). This IS the
    change-velocity separation that motivated DPQ (§9).

    **Why NOT "functional" and "infrastructure":**

    The initial framing used "functional policies → Rule"
    and "infrastructure qualifier → Qualifier." This is
    directionally correct but imprecise:

    - "Functional" collides with the GSM `Function`
      primitive. These Policies are not about Functions
      specifically — they are about **behavioral dynamics**
      (state mutations, event processing, sequencing).
      Functions are reached indirectly through Mechanism
      reference.
      **Behavioral** is the precise term.

    - "Infrastructure qualifier" is too narrow. Qualifiers
      exist on ALL SystemicPrimitives across ALL layers:
      Component (infrastructure), Function (organization),
      Purpose (constitution), Relationship (organization).
      The structural-defined category encompasses **any**
      primitive's Qualifier properties, not just
      infrastructure. **Primitive qualifier** is the
      precise scope.

    **However**: Organization IS the logical structuring OF
    Infrastructure. Structural properties on Organization-
    level primitives (e.g., maxConcurrency on Function,
    slaUptime on Relationship) are ultimately properties of
    the Infrastructure primitives that realize them
    (Mechanism, Channel). The meta-model allows Qualifiers
    on any SystemicPrimitive, but the structural truth lives
    at the Infrastructure layer. Organization-level
    structural Qualifiers are governance projections of
    Infrastructure properties.

    Properties that seem "organizational" but are really
    structural (maxConcurrency, slaUptime) CAN and arguably
    SHOULD be expressed on the Infrastructure primitives
    that carry them (Mechanism, Channel), not on the
    Organization-level abstractions (Function, Relationship)
    that govern them. This aligns with the vertical
    governance axes: governance constraints flow downward,
    structural reality flows upward.

    **Properties that are NOT qualifiers:**
    Some properties belong as encoded attributes of their
    primitive, not as qualifiers. Example: priority on
    Purpose — priority is an intrinsic definitional property
    of Purpose, not an extensible domain attribute. It
    should be a first-class property of Purpose if it is
    universally meaningful.

    **Category 3 — Structural-Emergent Policies (DP only)**

    Target: **model graph properties** — cardinality,
    existence, topology, composition structure. These are
    NOT Qualifier values and NOT runtime state. They are
    emergent properties derivable from the definition graph.

    Governance response: **none** (no definition atom). The
    DP chain terminates at Policy. Supervision evaluates the
    predicate directly against the model graph.

    Why no terminal: the governed property is not authored
    (unlike Qualifier values) and not maintained at runtime
    (unlike state objects). It is **structurally emergent**
    from governance decisions already made (composing
    Components, defining Purposes, wiring Interactions).
    No additional definition atom bridges the gap — the
    gap doesn't exist.

    Examples:
    - `size(System.components) >= 3` (composition cardinality)
    - `System.purposes.exists(p, p.name == "monitoring")`
      (constitutional completeness)
    - `size(Interface.receptors) >= 1` (interface coverage
      — already a consistency rule in the Interface note)

    **Partial DPQ absorption (open question):**
    Some structural-emergent constraints COULD become DPQ
    if the INTENT is made explicit via Qualifier:
    - Qualifier: {"minComponents": 3} on the System
    - Policy: `size(System.components) >= System.minComponents`
    This separates intent (what we want — Qualifier) from
    reality (what we have — graph property). Supervision
    verifies both: does intent satisfy bounds? does reality
    match intent? This gives governance signals earlier in
    the definitional process — before composition is
    actually articulated.

    **Dual governance — same constraint, both terminals:**

    A single Policy MAY produce BOTH a DPR chain (behavioral
    definition) AND a DPQ chain (structural definition).
    These are complementary, not alternative:

    - Policy: `Database.replicas >= 3`
    - DPQ: Qualifier {"replicas": 5} — structural
      DEFINITION (what we want the system to be)
    - DPR: Rule on("DatabaseProvisioned") → sys.create(
      "Database", {"replicas": qualifier.replicas}) —
      behavioral DEFINITION (how the system acts to realize
      the structural intent)

    Both are design-time definitions:
    - The Qualifier defines structural intent (authored
      value, verifiable at definition-time).
    - The Rule defines operational behavior (what happens
      when a provisioning event occurs).
    - The Supervision plane verifies Policy compliance:
      - Definition-time: does Qualifier value ≥ 3? ✓
      - Observation-time: does observed state match
        defined intent? (requires runtime evidence)

    The earlier framing ("DPQ for design-time definition,
    DPR for runtime enforcement") was incorrect: both are
    design-time definitions. The difference is what they
    define (structure vs. behavior) and when the Supervision
    plane can verify compliance (definition-time vs.
    observation-time).

    **Governance velocity — the unifying distinction:**

    Rule and Qualifier occupy the SAME governance velocity
    position relative to Policy:

    | Artifact  | Gov. velocity | Authority    | Gov. modality          | Technical modality |
    |-----------|---------------|--------------|------------------------|--------------------|
    | Policy    | Slow (gov.)   | Regulatory   | Declarative (constrains) | CEL predicate    |
    | Rule      | Fast (oper.)  | Operational  | Imperative (defines)     | Starlark code    |
    | Qualifier | Fast (oper.)  | Operational  | Imperative (defines)     | JSON data        |

    **Two modality axes (orthogonal):**
    - **Governance modality**: constraining (declarative) vs.
      defining (imperative). This is the governance-relevant
      distinction. Policy constrains — it declares bounds.
      Rule and Qualifier both define — they select specific
      variety within those bounds. Both are governance-
      imperative: acts of definition, not acts of constraint.
    - **Technical modality**: how the artifact is expressed
      (executable code vs. static data vs. predicate). This
      is an implementation concern, not a governance concern.

    Qualifier is governance-imperative despite being
    technically expressed as static JSON data. "This value
    IS 5" is an act of definition — it commands reality
    toward a specific configuration, just as "on this event,
    DO this" does. Neither constrains; both define.

    Policy is the governance-level constraint (changes
    slowly, regulatory authority, reviewed by governance
    processes). Rule and Qualifier are operational-level
    definitions (change faster, operational authority,
    different review processes).

    This velocity separation IS the core argument for DPQ:
    structural values (Qualifier) should have the same
    governance velocity independence from Policy as
    behavioral logic (Rule) has. Different profiles author
    them, in different temporal rhythms and system scopes.

    Collapsing Qualifier into Policy `==` (Resolution A,
    §5) conflates governance-velocity artifacts (Policy,
    slow) with operational-velocity artifacts (Qualifier,
    fast) in the same primitive — mixing two governance
    authorities in one artifact.

    **Both DPR and DPQ share the same governance modality
    transition:** DP (declarative: constraining) → terminal
    atom (imperative: defining). The fork from Policy to
    Rule or Qualifier is — in both chains — the declarative
    → imperative transition. They differ only in technical
    modality (code vs. data) and governance axis (behavioral
    vs. structural).

    **Determinism of the classification:**

    The category is determined by **static analysis of the
    Policy predicate** at save/parse time:

    1. Resolve all archetype property references in the
       predicate.
    2. If ANY reference targets a StateObjectArchetype
       property → **Behavioral** (DPR).
    3. If ALL references target Qualifier-bound properties
       on SystemicPrimitives → **Structural-defined** (DPQ).
    4. If ALL references target model graph properties
       (size(), exists(), cardinality on composition/
       relationship links) → **Structural-emergent** (DP).
    5. Mixed references → Policy may participate in
       multiple chains (dual governance).

    The Definition Manager can classify Policies
    automatically. No author-declared category needed —
    the predicate target IS the category.

    **Summary — the complete DP → {R, Q, —} grammar:**

    ```
    DP (constraining gradient — declarative, universal):
      Directive → Policy

    DPR (behavioral definition — imperative, code):
      DP → Rule (defines behavior) → Controller/Actuator/Sensor

    DPQ (structural definition — imperative, data):
      DP → Qualifier (defines value) → SystemicPrimitive

    DP-only (structural-emergent — no definition atom):
      DP → (Supervision verifies directly)
    ```

    This triple classification exhausts the Policy
    predicate target space. Every Policy predicate
    references either state-plane objects (behavioral),
    qualifier-defined properties (structural-defined), or
    model-graph properties (structural-emergent) — or a
    combination (dual governance).

    **Mapping to §10 relationship types:**
    - DPR: ENFORCEMENT (Rule ← Policy)
    - DPQ: SATISFACTION (Qualifier ← Policy)
    - DP-only: EVALUATION (no definition atom; Supervision
      evaluates predicate against definition graph)
  end note
